As @gabikliot stated, one can delay deactivation, but I didn't think deactivation would be an issue in this case.  Deactivation does not occur immediately after all messages are processed.  Grains waits a period of time before deactivating, known as the collection age.

The default is 2 hours, but is configurable by setting the collection age limit.
ClusterConfiguration.Globals.Application.SetDefaultCollectionAgeLimit or for per grain type limits
ClusterConfiguration.Globals.Application.SetCollectionAgeLimit.

The system will deactivate the grain after the grain has received no grain calls for the collection age limit.  So by default it will wait 2 hours after the start call before shutting down the grain, well past the expected 40 seconds necessary to perform the operation.

If you've a strong concern about the grain shutting itself down, you can expose the web calls as part of the grain interface and have the grain call itself, but this is less performant.  Since each web call is performed as a grain call, the grain will always have messages to process until all of the web calls are complete.  Something like the below:

    public interface ITestRunnerGrain : IGrainWithIntegerKey
    {
        Task StartTest(int count);
        Task HttpCall(int callId, int max);
    }

    public class TestRunnerGrain : Grain, ITestRunnerGrain 
    {
        public Task StartTest(int count)
        {
            CallNext(0,count);
            return TaskDone.Done;
        }

        private async Task HttpCall(int callId, int max)
        {
            await HttpCall();
            callId++;
            CallNext(callId,count);
        }

        private void CallNext(int callId, int max)
        {
            if(callId < max)
            {
                GrainFactory.GetGrain<ITestRunnerGrain>(GetPrimaryKeyLong()).HttpCall(callId,max).Ignore();
            }
        }
    }

* I stress, this should not be necessary with even a 5 minute collection age.

